1¶

Perform Explanatory Data Analysis on the dataset. Extract various insights from data by visualizing via different and suitable charts. Also explain the data-set verbally.

This data-set is actually consisting of several observations for 3333 customers of a bank. The first 19 columns are informations related to customers' experience with bank and usage of bank products, properties, cards, applications etc. The last column called churn is an indicator variable whether the customer have had left the bank in a specified time period unknown to the researcher. The columns can be briefly explained as,

account length: for how many months does the customer have the account, an integer nominal variable

location code: code of the location of the customer on bank records, a categorical variable

user id: customer's special number on bank records, a categorical variable with 3333 different categories

credit card info save: whether if customer has had their cards information saved in an application/web-page, a binary indicator variable

push status: whether if customer has allowed the bank to send notifications, a binary indicator variable

add to wishlist: number of items/products added by the customer to the wishlist, an integer nominal variable

desktop sessions: number of sessions in bank account opened on computer by customer, an integer nominal variable

app sessions: number of sessions in bank account opened on mobile application by customer, an integer nominal variable

desktop transactions: number of money transactions performed by the customer on computer, an integer nominal variable

total product detail reviews: number of times customer reviewed a product or service offered, an integer nominal variable

session duration: total or average time spent by the customer on web and mobile applications of bank, an integer nominal variable

promotion clicks: number of times the customer have been interested and clicked on a promotion offer, an integer nominal variable

avg order value: average cost/price of shopping made by the customer, an continuous nominal variable

sale product views: number of times customer reviewed a product or service that is on sale, an integer nominal variable

discount rate per visited products: average discount rates of the products the moment the customer visited, a continuous nominal variable

product detail view per app session: ratio of number product detail views to number of application sessions of customer, a continuous nominal variable

app transactions: number of money transactions performed by the customer on mobile application, an integer nominal variable

add to cart per session: how many things are added to card by the customer on average each session, a continuous nominal variable

customer service calls: how many times has the customer called the service, an integer nominal variable

churn: the indicator variable of whether the customer has left the bank

It is also useful to see how many different location codes exist in the dataset.

As a first step, for the numerical variables histograms can be visualized,

In [11]:
selected_cols = [0]
colors = ['mediumvioletred']
for i in range(15): 
    selected_cols.append(i+5) 
    colors.append('#%06X' % randint(0, 0xFFFFFF))

fig, axes = plt.subplots(5,3, figsize=(24,24))
fig.suptitle("Histograms of Various Features", size=48)
for i in range(5):
    for j in range(3):
        sns.histplot(data1.iloc[:,selected_cols[3*i+j]], ax=axes[i,j], color=colors[3*i+j], kde=True)

It can be seen that most of the variables are distributed roughly normally which is a fair assumption for learning tasks. Nevertheless there are some interesting behavior with 'add to wish list', 'app transactions' and 'customer service calls'

It is shown that most people do not add anything to their wishlist, either they do not know the feature or not find it useful. Other people use the feature frequently on the contrary as, there is actually an approximate normal distribution with mean 30 and +-20 tails.

App transactions is an integer variable with highly clustered bins. Moreover, the distribution is not near normal bu more like Erlang with small k. It can also be interpreted as a normal distribution that is right skewed where median can be a better indicator of general tendency compared to the mean because of outliers on a small range.

Customer service calls show a similar behaviour too. It can be said that on average customers call service 1 or 2 times. But there are outlier values. Also this variable is highly clustered over a short number of integer values. It can be argued that this attribute can also be taken as categorical. Nevertheless, it is very probable that increase, decrease or a certain limit in the number of service calls might mean something for the target variable. Hence, the nominality of the variable will be preserved.

The groups in desktop transactions are also somewhat discrete demonstrating an interesting behavior. Also, there is a slight increase in the value of 0 for product detail view per app session and add to cart per session. This might also mean that some customers either they do not know the these features or not find them to be of use.

Also for categorical variables count of categories can be shown,

It is obvious that location does not lead to any different behaviours in the customers. The boxplots are the same of each other for every variable. Furthermore, mean values and outlier attributes can easily be seen.

Desktop session mean is 175, app session mean is 30. Both attributes are a little less varied in location 408 comparably.

Product detail view per app session is distributed the same everywhere with average 11, add to cart per session is nearly 3 for customers.

As mentioned before, there are many outliers for app transactions and service calls above the mean value.

For the same variables, it can be questioned whether the distribution changes for the "churn" customers. If splitted violin plots are visualized,

In [15]:
colors = ['cornflowerblue']

For most of the features, it can be seen that the distributions are the same with each other hinting that these features might not have much importance in understanding the reason behind the churn or predicting a model.

For desktop sessions and app sessions, same case is demonstrated. Though there are churn for all parameters, most of the churn are in two clusters with one's mean near the actual mean of the variable and other cluster's mean on a higher value. This reveals that though app sessions or desktop sessions are not the single driver of the churn, being above some threshold in these variables might increase the possiblity of churn.

Product detail view per app session and add to cart per session show a somewhat similar characteristic. However, the analogy is weak as the second cluster may not be statistically significant on some level of comparison.

The most striking difference is in the customer service calls, while the normal (churn 0) customers are distributed very similar to the overall distribution of this variable, it can be examined that the distribution of churn customers are really different with wider distribution averaging 1-2 and a second distribution created on mean 4. This illustrates that the customer service calls of churn customers can come from any service call value or customers calling service more might tend to churn because their percentage in churn distribution seem to be higher than the one in the overall distribution.

Another question can be whether increase or decrease in the level of variables increase the likelihood of churn. Since most variables are continuous or integer values continuous, all variables are seperated into 5 equi-spaced bins of increasing mean value. Then, percentage of churn in each bins are demonstrated on bar graph.

For the three categorical variables, percentage of churn in each category is demonstrated on the below 3 graphs.

For most variables, change in the level can not be associated with an increase in probability of churn.

As mentioned before, for the desktop sessions app sessions there is a boundary after which the churn rates increase significantly. Session duration and product detail view per app session show a like-wise case, but probabilities do not change that drastically. There are other small changes with the change in levels of some features but these are small and can be ignored.

The churn rates seem to be approximately same for locations. Saving the credit card info and not allowing for push notifications seem to be significant in increasing the churn probability for a customer.

Lastly, the correlations between columns can be demonstrated,

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12,12))

Out[17]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7f12f4ea7810>

The correlogram illustrates some strange patterns. For most of the variables there is no relationship in between.

On the other hand, add to wish list and push notifications seem to be almost perfectly positively correlated. Perhaps this is because items that are added to the wishlist are recognized by the customers usually when a notification is sent.

Also app and desktop sessions seem to be perfectly correlated. This actually explains the high extent of similarity in the features' behaviors with churn and location code as well as the similarity of distributions.

Session duration and product detail views are correlated perfectly. Probably because viewing products always increase the session time and this process takes roughly the same time for each customer.

Discount rate per visited products is in perfect positive correlation with average order value. This can mean that customers tendency to buy products increase with discount rate.

Lastly, a similar association can be demonstrated between product detail per app session and add to cart per session, meaning that people tend to add the products they view more into the cart.

Interestingly, churn is weakly positively correlated with desktop and app sessions (they are the similar measures) and customer service calls. Moreover, as illustrated by the previous charts, there is weak positive association between saving credit card information and churn and weak negative association between allowing for push notifications and churn.

Normally after this step it would be meaningful to illustrate some bubble plots and show the churn using 3-dimensions including size. However, the correlations are either non-existent or perfect. So, plotting bubble plots or scatter plots will not yield any useful information.

2¶

Perform feature selection before modelling the data.

It is obvious that the user id can not be an indicator of churn because it is specific to the customer and probably the IDs are not given by a rule related to age, gender, money, social class etc. Hence, user id column will be eliminated.

From the remaining features, although it seemed that the location code can be useful, it is seen via the detailed charts in the previous part that the location does not alter the distributions or change the rate of churn. This column will also be eliminated from the data. If this column were to be kept, then one-hot encoding would be needed.

From the visualizations in previous part, it is obvious that features such as desktop sessions, app sessions, credit card info save and push status can be important factors affecting churn rates. Also, product detail views, session duration, discount and sale product views seem to indicate change in percentage of churn at some levels, though weakly.

From the remaining features, the distribution for desktop transactions and promotion clicks are the same. Moreover, change in the promotion click amount do not seem to signal any change in churn behaviour from the barplot. It can be stated that these variables might not be of much importance in determination of churn. The distributions are also approximately the same for avg order value and this feature is moving with discount rate per visited products. Hence, keeping it in the model may not be necessary. These features also will not be selected.

The remaining features are kept and from feature selection 14 features are selected.

In [18]:
features = pd.get_dummies(data1).drop(['user id', 'location code', 'desktop transactions', 'promotion clicks', 'avg order value'], axis=1)
feature_list = list(features.drop('churn', axis=1).columns)
features = features.to_numpy()

3¶

Create to models to fit and predict the churn variable with algorithms random forest and xgboost. Analyse the model via variable importance module and explain the most important features in model building by visualizing a bar chart.

Though a widely used methodology, decision trees are prone to over-fitting and usually the performance drops significantly in the testing stage. There are some parameters that can eliminate over-fitting to a certain degree such as keeping the depth of the tree small, not allowing for further seperations when a certain number of observations are present in the node (pre-prunning), not allowing for a node to split if at least one of the resultant nodes have a number of observations smaller than a specified threshold (post-prunning) and setting a necessary amount of the impurity before-hand.

Another possibility is to execute cross-validation to create a large tree and then prunning the large tree backwards. Cross validation is a methodology that is widely used for many statistical learning algorithms. It is preferred over train-test approach because of its allowance for changing the model at an early stage and using different batches of dataset to reduce over-fitting. Nevertheless, since the algorithms to be used are already ensemble algorithms, it is regarded enough by the researcher to use train-test approach.

Random Forest¶

Random forest is an ensemble bagging algorithm that helps create several random trees with different feature selections and branching. The predictions are made via majority voting between the trees created.

For this part, %20 of the data is seperated to be used in testing, while %80 will be used in model building.

In [19]:
X_train, X_test, Y_train, Y_test = train_test_split(features[:,:-1], features[:,-1:], test_size=0.2)

As the dataset is not very big, 5 trees are seen as enough for the forest. For each tree, to reduce the possiblity of over-fitting maximum depth is limited to 6 and it is not allowed for nodes to further seperate if they contain less than 20 observations.

In [20]:

forest.fit(X_train, Y_train)

Although random state is set for repeatability, in most of the cases the main features with highest importances are the same. As also revealed in the EDA process; app sessions and desktop sessions are both important for the model.

It has been observed in the violin-plots that the distribution of customer service calls changes drrastically for churn and non-churn customer populations, this drastic change is reflected in the importances of the random forest model as customer service calls are almost always the most or the second most important fearture in models.

Credit card info save, as shown by the barplots of percentage of churn in EDA has been an important determinant on predicting churn.

Moreover, app transactions, session duration, product detail view per app session and discount rate per visited products are features that usually come off as somewhat important in several models. It has been expected for session duration, product detail view per app session and discount rate per visited products to be important as barplots and splitted violinplots have hinted a change before. However, selection of app transactions has been surprising.

Account length, sale product views and total product views are usually features with too little importance. This might be an expected result as change in levels or being on a certain level do not change the percentage of churn in a statistically significant manner.

XG Boost¶

XGBoost is an ensemble boosting algorithm that is named after Gradient Boosting and makes use of learning rate as well as **regularization while creating different trees. Although depending on tree structure and ensembling trees, XGBoost is built different compared to the random forest.

Nevertheless, there are some parameters that can be adjusted in XGBoost to make the probability of over-fitting decrease. Just like random forest maximum depth of the trees, number of the trees, learning rate, the objective function (in this case there is binary target variable) and the regularizer parameter alpha is given.

When the splitted data is used to train a XGBoost model,

In [108]:

xg_cl.fit(X_train,Y_train)

Interestingly, the feature importances vary a lot from one instance to another compared to the experiments with random forest. This reveals an underlying difference between the two methodologies. In this case as the accuracy has been higher and the feature importances have been less variant, random forest is a safer option to build a model.

When the graphs of different XGBoost models are inspected, desktop and app sessions are again good determinants. Furthermore, as illustrated by the random forest, discount rate per visited products is in general one of the important features. However, the importance of customer service calls and credit card info save are almost usually non-existent or very weak.

Another surprising result is that account length and session duration are usually more important in these models, decreasing the trust into modelling the dataset with this methodology because these variables have not seemed much important in EDA process.

Compare the models on 0.6 versus 0.8 train sizes for both models.

In [24]:
forest1 = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=5, max_depth=6, min_samples_split=20, random_state=4)

It can be seen that the accuracy in the test period is roughly the same. There is an increase that is very small and attaining the same level a good thing. When building some models, if the models are prone to over-fitting increase in the size of the training set increases the generalization ability of the model and hence decreases the test period error rate. If there were any over-fitting in the models, the classification accuracy of the model with larger training set (0.8) would have been significantly better than the classification accuracy of the model with smaller training set (0.6). It can be concluded that both models are useful with approximately same performance.

6¶

The zip codes in USA are normally 5-digits, why are these zip codes are 4-digits? Find an explanation and fix the codes accordingly.

For this question, an answer is checked first on the Kaggle page of the data-set. However, no relevant answers were found there as probably zip code is not a numeric attribute but rather a categorical one and missing 1 digit in all observations is not of much importance in analysis and model fitting. However, when an answer is searched on Google, it is revealed that the zip codes in Boston have a leading zero. This zero might have been probably lost in recording the data on some medium as the data type can easily be confused to be a numerical one. Hence, leading zeros are added to fill for the fifth digit,

In [36]:
data2['Public_Schools']['ZIPCODE'] = data2['Public_Schools']['ZIPCODE'].apply(lambda x: str(x).zfill(5))

Algorithm Skills¶

There are two questions in this set.

1¶

Find an algorithm that finds the smallest of three numbers given as inputs.

Basically, if a number is not smaller than both of the others at the same time, then there are two candidates left being the smallest. If these candidates are compared with each other, the minimum input is found.

In [118]:
def minimum():
    num1 = float(input())
    print("First input taken as", num1)
    num2 = float(input())
    print("Second input taken as", num2)
    num3 = float(input())
    print("Last input taken as", num3)
    print("Smallest number is ")
    if num1 <= num2 and num1 <= num3:
        print(str(num1))
    elif num2 <= num3:
        print(str(num2))
    else:
        print(str(num3))

2¶

Write an algorithm that finds the name of the city with the largest number of vowels (A, E, I, O, U ) in it in the Police data set. Also, calculate the average number of vowels per city name.

For both tasks, counting number of vowels for a given string is required. A function is created to help purpose that ignores the lower-upper.

In [53]:
def vowel(word):
    count = 0
    for i in list(word.lower()):
        if i in list(('a', 'e', 'i', 'u', 'o')):
            count += 1
    return count

Both tasks also require iterating over the data and calculating the number of vowels for each city name. So a data-frame is created beforehand.

In [54]:
vowels = pd.DataFrame(np.unique(data2['Police']['City']), columns=['City'])
vowels['Vowels'] = np.zeros(len(vowels))

highest = 0
index = 0
for i in range(0, len(vowels)):
    city_vowels = vowel(vowels['City'][i])
    vowels['Vowels'][i] = city_vowels/len(vowels['City'][i])
    if city_vowels > highest:
        highest = city_vowels
        index = i

Social Science Skills¶

Name 5 variables that might affect the demand in the products of an e-commerce company with reasons. (ex. 'Price')

  1. Price

Not only in e-commerce setting but in all free-markets with competition, price is important. People have a marginal boundary for each product and service based on most factors such as their needs, personalities, wealth and socio-economic status. A price that is above the boundary for a product, will eventually decrease the demand in the product.

On the other hand, cheaper products might attract more people but there are also another constraints for the company to operate with profit because of costs of production.

  1. Seasonality

Not all, but demand for some products can change drastically or slightly through seasons. Best examples are; sun-glasses, air coolers, scarves, iced-tea and boots. The seasonality does not always need to refer to a specific season, sometimes a special day, holiday, week or festival can also affect the demand for a product.

Such as the increase in demand for flowers around Mothers Day and Valentines Day or more bicycles bought at the beginning of school holidays. Nevertheless, this is also not only the case for e-commerce companies.

  1. Special Events and Campaigns

Announcing a decrease in the price is usually a demand-increaser because it will signal a profitable exchange for people even if the price is still high for the product. Many companies but mostly the e-commerce giants, use such strategies like Mega Discount Days or Ultra Surprise Discount Week for several categories of products to increase the demand. Which actually lead people to postpone their shoppings till the event or create a non-existent demand because of the perception and in turn increase the demand.

This is also suitable for non-e-commerce companies but mostly used in e-commerce. Moreover, its interaction with the price and seasonality is also worth inspecting.

  1. Layout, Ease of Use and Interface of the Website

E-commerce means shopping online. This encompasses not only the process of placing an order but also searching for the most suitable, useful, profitable or satisfying product. Web-pages with disturbing layout, complicated design or hard to use interface might be repulsive to look at or even to use. Another important factor is the amount of information provided and the accesibility of the information. Web-sites or applications with too little information or showing too many information at once might be uncomfortable to search and shop at.

  1. Cargo Company and Arrival Statistics of Orders

Searching for the best alternative and placing the order is not the end of the shopping. Lead time of arrival and the status of product arriving the customer is also very important. Cargo shipment companies are thought of as very problematic in Turkey and there are only small amount of people which have never encountered a problem with the delivery company or person. Hence, the choice with the company or, the satisfaction with the delivery system of the company if it has its own can be an important factor in determining the place to shop on e-commerce.

Other important factors can be quality of the products sold, variability of the products or services offered, competition level of the market of operation, past customer satisfaction rate, accessibility of product reviews, comments by the customer.
